children and split into two groups for the core subjects, such as English and Maths is a huge advantage to her. It does mean that she can thrive academically. A private school won't make a child bright if they aren't, but it should if it is a good one bring out the best in each child. The fees are outrageous really, but on the other hand I do think it is worth every penny. &#10;Can someone please tell me though why people assume that all children attending a private school come from rich, affluent backgrounds? Also why are they all deemed as being snooty? This is the biggest myth of all! &#10;DDS on the other hand is thriving in his state school. An independent education just was not right for him. He loves his school and he is only in a class of 10 as well. &#10;Don't know what we will do with DDD at senior level yet. Hopefully she will pass the entrance exam for the local (state) grammar school or the exam to a senior independent school. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1245" language="en" documentId="4675" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Victoria C(502)" date="01-02-12 22:54" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://www.netmums.com/coffeehouse/children-parenting-190/primary-school-age-4-11-years-60/713563-opinions-private-vs-state-schools-please-all.html" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="4675" notes="" title="opinions on private vs state schools please"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="172"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="173" end="679"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="680" end="894"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="895" end="1064"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="1065" end="1245"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55"/></xmi:XMI>